08207nam a22012495i 9783110198768DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1002262816  a(OCoLC)1004872183  a(OCoLC)1011460517  a(OCoLC)1013955548  a(OCoLC)987928857  a(OCoLC)992454449  a(OCoLC)999372199  a97831101987687 a10.1515/97831101987682doi  a(DE-B1597)34642  a(OCoLC)979583676  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP294.5.R43 2007aP294.5 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a415  aET 7502rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28029:00aRecent Advances in the Syntax and Semantics of Tense, Aspect and Modality /ced. by Jacques Moeschler, Genoveva Puskás, Louis de Saussure. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (253 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v1850 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is a fact that tense, aspect and modality together form one of the most recurring and active areas of research in contemporary syntax and semantics, as well as in other disciplines of linguistics. A large number of syntactic and semantic phenomena are concerned by the temporal-aspectual-modal level of representation: information about time, aspect and modality is part of virtually all sentences; inflexion is quite widely considered as the core of syntactic projections. Because of this very crucial situation and role in the sentence structure, temporal-aspectual and modal information concerns virtually any part of the sentence and this information has scope over the whole characterization of the eventuality denoted by the sentence. This book is an up-to-date milestone for the studies of temporality and language, in particular regarding syntax and semantics, but with incidental hints to pragmatics and theories of human natural language understanding. Through this very tight selection of 15 papers (originally delivered during the 6th Chronos colloquium), tenses, aspect and modality are investigated both at the descriptive and theoretical levels, involving many different Indo-European and non-Indo-European languages. The volume sheds light on a wide array of phenomena that remained too little explored until now. These include the following: modal subordination in Japanese, epistemic modals in Dutch and English in Free Indirect Speech contexts, aspectual readings of idioms, adverb-licensing with the German perfect, French imperfective past compared with English progressive past, infinitival perfect in English, Adult Root Infinitives, economy constraints on temporal subordinations, future modality, past interpretation of present tense in embedded clauses, and time without tenses in Mandarin and Navajo. The book is of interest to scholars and advanced students in the fields of linguistics (general linguistics, semantics, syntax) as well as philosophy and logic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxTemporal constructions. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxTense. 0aModality (Linguistics). 0aSemantics. 4aLinguistik. 4aSemantik. 4aSyntax. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGeneral linguistics.  asemantics.  asyntax.1 aAnand, Pranav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsher, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoogaart, Ronny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemirdache, Hamida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtxepare, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlasbey, Sheila, econtributor